## 4. Verifying Authentication Records

Modern email authentication uses three complementary standards. Failing any of them is a strong phishing indicator.

### SPF (Sender Policy Framework)

**What it does:** Specifies which IP addresses are authorized to send email on behalf of a domain.

**How to check:** Look for the `Authentication-Results:` or `Received-SPF:` header.

```
Received-SPF: Pass (domain of legitimate.com designates 203.0.113.1 as permitted sender)
Received-SPF: Fail (domain of legit.com does not designate 45.33.22.11 as permitted sender)
```

**SPF result meanings:**

| Result | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| `pass` | The sending IP is authorized |
| `fail` | The sending IP is NOT authorized — strong phishing indicator |
| `softfail` | The sending IP is probably not authorized (~all policy) |
| `neutral` | The domain owner has no policy stance |
| `none` | No SPF record found for the domain |
| `temperror` | Temporary DNS error |
| `permerror` | Permanent SPF record error (misconfiguration) |

**Manual SPF lookup:**

```bash
dig TXT example.com +short | grep spf
# or
nslookup -type=TXT example.com
```

**Example SPF record:**

```
v=spf1 include:_spf.google.com include:sendgrid.net ip4:203.0.113.0/24 -all
```

The `-all` at the end means "reject all senders not listed above" (strict). `~all` is softfail (lenient). `+all` (dangerous) allows anyone.

---

### DKIM (DomainKeys Identified Mail)

**What it does:** Digitally signs the email with a private key. The recipient verifies the signature using a public key published in DNS.

**How to check:** Look for `DKIM-Signature:` headers and the result in `Authentication-Results:`.

```
Authentication-Results: mx.recipient.com;
       dkim=pass header.i=@legitimate.com header.s=selector1 header.b=AbCdEf12
```

```
Authentication-Results: mx.recipient.com;
       dkim=fail (signature did not verify) header.i=@spoofed.com
```

**DKIM result meanings:**

| Result | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| `pass` | Signature valid — email was not modified in transit |
| `fail` | Signature invalid — email was tampered with, or key mismatch |
| `none` | No DKIM signature present |
| `permerror` | Permanent error (misconfigured record) |
| `temperror` | Temporary DNS lookup failure |

**Manual DKIM key lookup:**

The `DKIM-Signature:` header contains a `s=` (selector) and `d=` (domain) value:

```
DKIM-Signature: v=1; a=rsa-sha256; d=example.com; s=selector1; ...
```

Look up the public key:

```bash
dig TXT selector1._domainkey.example.com +short
```

---

### DMARC (Domain-based Message Authentication, Reporting & Conformance)

**What it does:** Ties SPF and DKIM together and tells receiving mail servers what to do when a message fails authentication (nothing, quarantine, or reject).

**How to check:** Look in `Authentication-Results:` for `dmarc=`.

```
Authentication-Results: mx.recipient.com;
       dmarc=pass (p=REJECT) header.from=legitimate.com
```

```
Authentication-Results: mx.recipient.com;
       dmarc=fail (p=NONE) header.from=spoofed.com
```

**Manual DMARC record lookup:**

```bash
dig TXT _dmarc.example.com +short
```

**Example DMARC record:**

```
v=DMARC1; p=reject; rua=mailto:dmarc-reports@example.com; pct=100
```

**DMARC policy values:**

| Policy (`p=`) | Action on failure |
|---|---|
| `none` | No action taken — monitoring only |
| `quarantine` | Move to spam/junk folder |
| `reject` | Reject the message outright |

> **Note:** A domain with `p=none` provides **zero protection** against spoofing — attackers frequently target organizations with weak DMARC policies.

---

### Authentication Summary Table

| Scenario | SPF | DKIM | DMARC | Verdict |
|----------|-----|------|-------|---------|
| Legitimate email | pass | pass | pass | ✅ Likely legitimate |
| Compromised account | pass | pass | pass | ⚠️ Could still be phishing |
| Display name spoofing | pass | pass | fail | 🚨 Likely phishing |
| Domain spoofing | fail | none | fail | 🚨 Almost certainly phishing |
| Email forwarding | fail | pass | pass | ⚠️ Possibly legitimate (forwarding breaks SPF) |
| Third-party sender | pass | fail | pass | ⚠️ Investigate further |

