## 7. Analyzing Attachments

### Safe Handling Procedures

> ⚠️ Always analyze attachments in an **isolated environment** — a dedicated analysis VM, an online sandbox, or a containerized environment. Never open on your primary system.

**Before opening anything:**

1. Note the file type (look at extension AND magic bytes — they may differ)
2. Calculate file hashes for threat intel lookups
3. Submit to an online sandbox first

**Calculate file hashes:**

```bash
# Linux/macOS
sha256sum suspicious_attachment.pdf
md5sum suspicious_attachment.pdf

# Windows PowerShell
Get-FileHash suspicious_attachment.pdf -Algorithm SHA256
Get-FileHash suspicious_attachment.pdf -Algorithm MD5
```

Search hashes in:
- VirusTotal: `https://www.virustotal.com/gui/file/[SHA256]`
- Hybrid Analysis: `https://www.hybrid-analysis.com`

### Common Malicious Attachment Types

| File Type | Common Threats | Analysis Tool |
|-----------|---------------|---------------|
| `.docx` / `.doc` | Malicious macros, template injection | OLETools (`olevba`) |
| `.xlsm` / `.xls` | Macro-enabled spreadsheets, XLM macros | OLETools (`xlmdeobfuscator`) |
| `.pdf` | Embedded JavaScript, launch actions, URIs | PDFiD, pdf-parser |
| `.html` / `.htm` | Credential harvesting pages, smuggled payloads | Browser sandbox |
| `.zip` / `.rar` | Packed malware, password-protected payloads | Extract and analyze contents |
| `.iso` / `.img` | Used to bypass Mark-of-the-Web; contain LNK or EXE | Mount and analyze |
| `.lnk` | LNK files that execute PowerShell or cmd.exe | lnkparse, LECmd |
| `.js` / `.vbs` | Dropper scripts | Any.run, manual review |
| `.exe` / `.dll` | Direct malware delivery | Sandbox, Ghidra, x64dbg |

### Analyzing Office Documents (OLETools)

```bash
# Install OLETools
pip install oletools

# Check for suspicious indicators (high-level overview)
mraptor suspicious.docx

# Extract VBA macro code
olevba suspicious.docx

# Check for OLE objects and embedded content
oleid suspicious.docx

# Analyze all streams
oledump.py suspicious.docx
```

**Suspicious macro indicators:**

```vba
' Dangerous functions to look for:
Shell()           ' Executes system commands
CreateObject()    ' Creates COM objects (often WScript.Shell)
AutoOpen()        ' Runs automatically when document is opened
Document_Open()   ' Runs automatically in Word
Workbook_Open()   ' Runs automatically in Excel
PowerShell        ' Often used to download and execute payloads
Environ()         ' Accesses environment variables
Chr()             ' Character encoding to obfuscate strings
```

### Analyzing PDFs

```bash
# Install PDF tools
pip install pdfminer.six
# Download PDFiD and pdf-parser from https://blog.didierstevens.com

# Quick overview of suspicious elements
python pdfid.py suspicious.pdf

# Look for JavaScript specifically
python pdfid.py suspicious.pdf | grep -i javascript

# Parse and extract JavaScript from a PDF
python pdf-parser.py -s JavaScript suspicious.pdf

# Extract all streams
python pdf-parser.py -a suspicious.pdf
```

**Suspicious PDF indicators:**

```
/JS           - Contains JavaScript
/JavaScript   - Contains JavaScript action
/AA           - Additional Actions (triggers)
/OpenAction   - Runs automatically when opened
/Launch       - Can launch applications
/URI          - Contains URLs
/EmbeddedFile - Contains embedded files
/RichMedia    - Can contain Flash (legacy)
```

### HTML Attachment Analysis

HTML attachments are increasingly used for phishing because:

- They can host complete phishing pages locally (bypassing URL filters)
- They can use JavaScript to decode and render obfuscated content
- They may use HTML smuggling to drop files on disk

```bash
# View HTML source — look for:
# 1. Embedded base64 data blobs
# 2. Obfuscated JavaScript
# 3. Form actions pointing to external URLs
# 4. atob() calls (base64 decode in JavaScript)

# Example of HTML smuggling pattern:
grep -i "atob\|fromCharCode\|eval\|unescape" suspicious.html
```

