## 8. Identifying Social Engineering Tactics

Understanding the psychological techniques used in phishing emails helps with triage and user awareness.

### Common Psychological Triggers

| Tactic | Example | What to look for |
|--------|---------|-----------------|
| **Urgency** | "Your account will be suspended in 24 hours" | Time pressure, countdown language |
| **Fear** | "Unauthorized access detected on your account" | Alarm language, security alerts |
| **Authority** | Impersonation of CEO, IT, IRS, police | Executive names, official logos |
| **Scarcity** | "Only 2 spots remaining — act now" | Limited time/quantity claims |
| **Social proof** | "Your colleagues have already verified" | Peer pressure language |
| **Curiosity** | "You have a pending document" | Vague but enticing subject lines |
| **Reciprocity** | "You've been selected for a reward" | Gift cards, prizes, refunds |

### Subject Line Red Flags

```
"Urgent: Action Required"
"Your account has been compromised"
"Invoice #[number] attached"
"Shared document: [believable filename]"
"RE: [meeting or project name]" (reply-chain spoofing)
"[Your company name] IT Security Alert"
"You have a new voicemail"
"Payment confirmation"
```

### Body Content Red Flags

- Generic greetings ("Dear Customer", "Dear User") instead of the recipient's name
- Grammar and spelling errors (though AI-generated phishing is now more polished)
- Requests for credentials, personal information, or wire transfers
- Mismatched or inconsistent branding (wrong logo, colors, fonts)
- Footer discrepancies (wrong address, phone number, legal text)
- Calls to action that bypass normal processes ("Don't use the normal system — reply directly to me")

### BEC (Business Email Compromise) Indicators

BEC attacks specifically target organizations for financial fraud. Key indicators:

- Email from a spoofed or look-alike executive email address
- Request to change banking/payment details for a vendor
- Urgent wire transfer request outside normal approval workflows
- "Confidential — don't tell anyone else about this"
- Sent from a free email provider claiming to be a company executive
- Requests involving gift cards (common in lower-value BEC scams)

